Because most breast cancer starts in a milk duct, scientists had theorized that flushing those ducts with fluid might draw out cancerous cells even before they could be spotted on a mammogram. Mammograms work very well at detecting early breast cancer, but they 're not perfect. Doctors put an anesthetic on the nipple and inserted a threadlike catheter to flush milk ducts with fluid that dislodges and draws out cells. The test uncovered clear cancer signs in just 13 percent of the cancerous breasts tested, and possible signs in 42 percent. 